                            <comment id="15395617" author="apachespark" created="Wed, 27 Jul 2016 12:54:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;User &apos;a-roberts&apos; has created a pull request for this issue:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/14379&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/14379&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15396641" author="srowen" created="Wed, 27 Jul 2016 23:23:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We can do this, sure, but why is it Critical? tests have zero surface area for users, because users don&apos;t even consume tests.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15397181" author="aroberts" created="Thu, 28 Jul 2016 07:36:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;But they do download the jar which contains a CVE, so by either developing Spark or downloading it they have access to the attacks available with the CVE&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;-&amp;gt; Adam works for company X, Adam&apos;s company distributes Spark to its customers&lt;br/&gt;
-&amp;gt; Its customers now have this vulnerable version of derby on their system&lt;br/&gt;
-&amp;gt; A disgruntled employee at such a company decides to use their Spark install (derby 10.11.x being on the classpath) to cause damage outlined in the CVE info&lt;br/&gt;
-&amp;gt; Alternatively a user has access to a Spark service hosted on an external system which again will have the vulnerable derby on the classpath and can therefore cause damage outlined in the CVE&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15397865" author="srowen" created="Thu, 28 Jul 2016 17:31:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, I see from the PR that it&apos;s actually packaged. I don&apos;t know that it actually surfaces the attack vector in Spark in practice, but, let&apos;s just apply this of course.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
